1858, steam locomotives had been progressively banned from crowded areas and were no longer in service below 42nd Street, giving rise to the need for a new terminal."},{"content":"http://cdn.abclocal.go.com/images/wabc/cms_exf_2007/_video_wn_images/8937656_1280x720.jpg"},{"content":""},{"content":"Reborn as &#34;Grand Central Station,&#34; the depot&#39;s most prominent feature was its enormous train shed. Constructed of glass and steel, the 100-foot wide by 650-foot long structure rivaled the Eiffel Tower and Crystal Palace for primacy as the most dramatic engineering achievement of the 19th century."},{"content":"http://cdn.abclocal.go.com/images/wabc/cms_exf_2007/_video_wn_images/8937649_1280x720.jpg"},{"content":""},{"content":"The age of the steam locomotive was drawing to a close. A catastrophic train collision on January 8, 1902, in the smoke-filled Park Avenue tunnel killed seventeen and injured thirty-eight, causing a public outcry and increasing demand for electric trains."},{"content":"http://cdn.abclocal.go.com/images/wabc/cms_exf_2007/_video_wn_images/8937653_1280x720.jpg"},{"content":""},{"content":"It took 10 expensive years of excavation and construction. The railroad needed to invest in electrifying its rails, and carve deep into Manhattan&#39;s bedrock. Yet, in spite of the upheaval, rail service continued uninterrupted."},{"content":"http://cdn.abclocal.go.com/images/wabc/cms_exf_2007/_video_wn_images/8938490_1280x720.jpg"},{"content":""},{"content":"Grand Central Terminal officially opened to great fanfare at 12:01 am on Sunday, February 2, 1913, and more than 150,000 people visited the new terminal on its opening day. Although construction was not yet entirely complete, Grand Central Terminal had arrived and New York City would never be the same again."},{"content":"http://cdn.abclocal.go.com/images/wabc/cms_exf_2007/_video_wn_images/8938487_1280x720.jpg"},{"content":""},{"content":"As the neighborhood prospered in 1930, so did Grand Central. Grand Central Terminal at various times housed an art gallery, an art school, a newsreel movie theater, a rail history museum, and innumerable temporary exhibitions."},{"content":"http://cdn.abclocal.go.com/images/wabc/cms_exf_2007/_video_wn_images/8938605_1280x720.jpg"},{"content":""},{"content":"On August 2, 1967, New York City&#39;s recently established Landmarks Preservation Commission -- formed in response to the demolition of Pennsylvania Station -- designated Grand Central Terminal as a landmark, subject to the protection of law. The decision ensured the terminal&#39;s safety. For the moment."},{"content":"http://cdn.abclocal.go.com/images/wabc/cms_exf_2007/_video_wn_images/8937657_1280x720.jpg"},{"content":""},{"content":"Penn Central, the resultant conglomerate of a merger between the New York Central and Pennsylvania Railroads, leased Grand Central Terminal to developer UGP Properties, Inc. UGP proposed building a 55-story tower designed by Marcel Breuer above Grand Central in 1968. The terminal&#39;s facade would have been preserved, but rendered virtually invisible. The entire main waiting room and part of the main concourse would have been demolished."},{"content":"http://cdn.abclocal.go.com/images/wabc/cms_exf_2007/_video_wn_images/8937648_1280x720.jpg"},{"content":""},{"content":"Penn Central filed an &#36;8 million lawsuit against the city of New York, which was blocking the renovation. Litigation lasted for nearly a decade. City leaders, including Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis and Brendan Gill, rallied against changes to Grand Central Terminal. In December 1976, the national register of historic places named Grand Central Terminal as a national historic landmark."},{"content":"http://cdn.abclocal.go.com/images/wabc/cms_exf_2007/_video_wn_images/8938488_1280x720.jpg"},{"content":""},{"content":"The former main waiting room was also restored in accordance with the new master plan in 1992. It was inaugurated as a public exhibition and special events space."},{"content":"http://cdn.abclocal.go.com/images/wabc/cms_exf_2007/_video_wn_images/8938486_1280x720.jpg"},{"content":""},{"content":"Throughout the year, Vanderbilt Hall, the terminal&#39;s 12,000 square foot former main waiting room, is the site for ongoing free promotions and entertainment ranging from tennis exhibits to the annual holiday fair, which brings 72 craftsmen, artisans and international importers to the terminal, selling an outstanding array of merchandise for holiday gifts."},{"content":"http://cdn.abclocal.go.com/images/wabc/cms_exf_2007/_video_wn_images/8937650_1280x720.jpg"},{"content":""},{"content":"Restored back to its 1913 splendor, Grand Central has become a major New York destination. There are five restaurants and cocktail lounges, 20 casual eateries in the lower level dining concourse, gourmet foods from Grand Central Market and 50 unique specialty shops throughout the concourses -- all in addition to transportation."}],"Title":"Photo Gallery: Grand Central Over The Years Through Pictures | 7online.com"}},"Entity-Digest":"sha1:6OEIIBPN2ZN4ZKL5G4W2S56ENO7BBG7A"}}},"Container":{"Compressed":true,"Gzip-Metadata":{"Footer-Length":"8","Deflate-Length":"9752","Header-Length":"10","Inflated-CRC":"1846369999","Inflated-Length":"53139"},"Offset":"1171341","Filename":"CC-MAIN-20150226075801-00336-ip-10-28-5-156.ec2.internal.warc.gz"}}
